HTML id and class Attributes
HTML id and class attributes are used to specify identifiers and classes for elements on a webpage.

HTML id Attribute
The id attribute is used to specify a unique identifier for an element. It is used to target a specific element in CSS or JavaScript.

HTML class Attribute
The class attribute is used to specify one or more classes for an element. It is used to apply styles or behaviors to multiple elements that share the same class.

HTML Code Example

<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
  <title>HTML id and class Attributes</title>
  <link rel="stylesheet" href="style.css">
</head>
<body>
  <!-- id attribute -->
  <h1 id="header">Welcome to My Website</h1>

  <!-- class attribute -->
  <p class="paragraph">This is a paragraph of text.</p>
  <p class="paragraph highlight">This is another paragraph of text with highlight.</p>
</body>
</html>


CSS Code Example

#header {
  color: blue;
  font-size: 36px;
}

.paragraph {
  font-size: 18px;
  margin-bottom: 20px;
}

.highlight {
  background-color: yellow;
}


Real-time Examples
1. Unique identifier: The id attribute can be used to target a specific element in CSS or JavaScript, such as styling a header element with a unique id.
2. Applying styles to multiple elements: The class attribute can be used to apply styles to multiple elements that share the same class, such as styling multiple paragraphs with the same font size and margin.

Questions and Answers
Q1: What is the purpose of the id attribute?
A1: The id attribute is used to specify a unique identifier for an element.

Q2: What is the difference between id and class attributes?
A2: The id attribute is used to target a specific element, while the class attribute is used to target multiple elements that share the same class.

Q3: Can you use multiple id attributes with the same value on a single webpage?
A3: No, id attributes must be unique within a document. You cannot use multiple id attributes with the same value on a single webpage.

Q4: Can you use multiple classes for a single element?
A4: Yes, you can use multiple classes for a single element by separating the class names with spaces.

Q5: How can you target an element with a specific id or class in CSS?
A5: You can target an element with a specific id using the # symbol followed by the id name, and target an element with a specific class using the . symbol followed by the class name.